import numpy as np
np.random.seed(42) # Setting a seed for reproducibility

# Generate target_material using categorical distribution
target_materials = ['alu', 'gold', 'plastic', 'polypropylene', 'polystyrene']
p1 = [0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.05, 0.05] # Probabilities for each material
target_materials_generated = np.random.choice(target_materials, size=25, p=p1)

# Generate target thickness using lognormal distribution parameters obtained from dataset statistics
mu = np.log(1/np.sqrt(1 + 0.83^2)) # Mean
sigma = np.sqrt(np.log(1 + 0.83^2)) # Standard deviation
target_thickness_generated = np.random.lognormal(mean=mu, sigma=sigma, size=25) * (max - min) + min
min, max = 0, 4.69 # Min and Max values from dataset statistics

# Generate pulse width using lognormal distribution parameters obtained from dataset statistics
mu_pulse = np.log(1/np.sqrt(1 + 275^2)) # Mean
sigma_pulse = np.sqrt(np.log(1 + 275^2)) # Standard deviation
pulse_width_generated = np.random.lognormal(mean=mu_pulse, sigma=sigma_pulse, size=25) * (max - min) + min
min, max = 30, 12900 # Min and Max values from dataset statistics

# Generate energy using lognormal distribution parameters obtained from dataset statistics
mu_energy = np.log(1/np.sqrt(1 + 4.6^2)) # Mean
sigma_energy = np.sqrt(np.log(1 + 4.6^2)) # Standard deviation
energy_generated = np.random.lognormal(mean=mu_energy, sigma=sigma_energy, size=25) * (max - min) + min
min, max = 0, 97.78 # Min and Max values from dataset statistics

# Generate spot size using lognormal distribution parameters obtained from dataset statistics
mu_spot = np.log(1/np.sqrt(1 + 2.4^2)) # Mean
sigma_spot = np.sqrt(np.log(1 + 2.4^2)) # Standard deviation
spot_size_generated = np.random.lognormal(mean=mu_spot, sigma=sigma_spot, size=25) * (max - min) + min
min, max = 0, 6.71 # Min and Max values from dataset statistics

# Generate intensity using lognormal distribution parameters obtained from dataset statistics
mu_intensity = np.log(1/np.sqrt(1 + 9^2)) # Mean
sigma_intensity = np.sqrt(np.log(1 + 9^2)) # Standard deviation
intensity_generated = np.random.lognormal(mean=mu_intensity, sigma=sigma_intensity, size=25) * (max - min) + min
min, max = 0, 368416E+20 # Min and Max values from dataset statistics

# Generate power using lognormal distribution parameters obtained from dataset statistics
mu_power = np.log(1/np.sqrt(1 + 5^2)) # Mean
sigma_power = np.sqrt(np.log(1 + 5^2)) # Standard deviation
power_generated = np.random.lognormal(mean=mu_power, sigma=sigma_power, size=25) * (max - min) + min
min, max = 0, 3948E+20 # Min and Max values from dataset statistics

# Generate cutoff energy using lognormal distribution parameters obtained from dataset statistics
mu_cutoff = np.log(1/np.sqrt(1 + 5^2)) # Mean
sigma_cutoff = np.sqrt(np.log(1 + 5^2)) # Standard deviation
cutoff_energy_generated = np.random.lognormal(mean=mu_cutoff, sigma=sigma_cutoff, size=25) * (max - min) + min

print(samples_generated)
```

This code generates synthetic data using the statistical properties of the input dataset. The target materials are sampled from a categorical distribution with pre-defined probabilities for each material type. Target thickness and other features (pulse width, energy, spot size, intensity, power, cutoff energy) are generated using lognormal distributions based on their respective mean and standard deviation values obtained from dataset statistics. The final samples array is constructed by stacking these feature arrays along the last dimension.

The resulting synthetic data can be used for further analysis or as input to machine learning models. It is important to note that this code assumes a specific seed value (42) for reproducibility, so running the same code multiple times will produce identical results. You may change the seed value or remove it altogether if desired.
